│ THOUGHT: The miscompilation arises when foldBitCeil removes the guarding select and uses the ctlz result even if it has a result range that excludes zero, which can make   │
│ ctlz poison for x==0. To fix this without breaking expected folds, I will add a precise guard in foldBitCeil: if the matched ctlz instruction carries MD_range metadata     │
│ whose lower bound > 0 (i.e., excludes zero), bail out of the transform. I’ll insert this guard just before the ShouldDropNUW block and submit the patch.                    │
│                                                                                                                                                                             │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ sed -i '/^  if (ShouldDropNUW)/i \  // Bail out if ctlz result has range metadata that excludes zero; folding may propagate poison.\n  if (auto *I =                        │
│ dyn_cast<Instruction>(Ctlz)) {\n    if (MDNode *R = I->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)) {\n      if (auto *CI0 =                                                         │
│ mdconst::extract_or_null<ConstantInt>(R->getOperand(0))) {\n        if (CI0->getValue().ugt(0))\n          return nullptr;\n      }\n    }\n  }'                            │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp && submit-patch                                                                                                       │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                         │
